{{Notability|Company|date=October 2018}}
{{Infobox company | name = Alibris | logo =http://www3.alibris-static.com/images/red/nav/alibris-logo.gif | type = [[Private company|Private]] | key_people =Tommaso Trionfi, CEO | industry = [[Retail|Retail (Specialty)]] | products = [[Used book]]s, [[out-of-print book]]s, rare books. Also features used or collectible games, music and movies ([[album]]s, [[cassette tapes]], [[compact disc]]s, [[DVD]]s) | revenue = $100M (as of 8/15/13)<ref name=tie /> | owner = [[Oak Hill Capital Partners]] {{!}} AM Holding Inc. | num_employees = 20 (as of 2/1/17) | company_slogan = | foundation = 1997 in [[Emeryville, California]]<ref name=monsoon>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2010/02/22/daily27.html|title=Alibris to buy Oregon sales software company Monsoon|date=February 23, 2010|author=Steven E.F. Brown|newspaper=[[American City Business Journals|San Francisco Business Journal]]|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref> | location = [[Emeryville, California]] | homepage = {{URL|alibris.com}} }}
'''Alibris''' is an online store that sells new books, [[used book]]s, [[out-of-print book]]s, rare books, and other media through an online network of [[independent bookstore|independent booksellers]].
== History == Alibris was founded in 1997 by [[Martin Manley]] and incorporated in 1998. It grew out of Interloc, an online company founded by antiquarian bookseller Richard Weatherford in 1994.{{Better source|reason=Citation is the Alibris company website; there must be more objective sources for this.|date=October 2018}} Interloc was one of the earliest successful efforts to centralize used book data online.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} It remained a private network until 1996, when the company launched its website. The company was backed by venture capital until 2006, when it was purchased by [[Oak Hill Capital Partners]], a [[private equity firm]]. In February 2010, Oak Hill Capital Partners bought Monsoon and merged it with Alibris with Monsoon Commerce owning Alibris.<ref name=tie>{{cite web|url=https://oregon.tie.org/event/40/mentor-connect-kanth-gopalpur|title=Mentor Connect with Kanth Gopalpur|publisher=[[TiE|TiE Oregon]]|accessdate=January 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221104657/https://oregon.tie.org/event/40/mentor-connect-kanth-gopalpur|archive-date=2014-02-21|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> As of February 2017, Alibris was owned by AM Holding Inc. (formerly Monsoon Commerce Inc.){{citation needed|date=October 2018}}
== Company == Booksellers list their inventories on Alibris which in turn offers the books on its retail [[website]], a separate library services site, and business-to-business partners such as [[Barnes & Noble]], [[Books-A-Million]], and [[Chapters|Chapters Indigo]]. It also offers services in the UK with the [[Waterstones]] market place. It offers more than 150 million books from a network of over 15,000 booksellers in 65 countries.
Most sales made through Alibris are fulfilled by the bookseller directly to the end customer. Sales to libraries or other institutions or books needing transoceanic shipping are consolidated in a distribution center in [[Sparks, Nevada]]. Alibris also has a similar network for music ([[record album|albums]], [[cassette tapes]], and [[CDs]]) and movies ([[VHS]] or [[DVD]]).
Alibris allows customers to buy and sell at the same time. Alibris charges a starting fee that varies based on what is being sold and what kind of commission is charged.
Alibris was a charter member of the [[Google eBooks]] service when it was announced by Google on December 6, 2010.<ref name="googebook2010">{{cite web| url= http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/12/discover-more-than-3-million-google.html | title= Discover more than 3 million Google eBooks from your choice of booksellers and devices | work= Official blog | publisher=[[Google]] | date= December 6, 2010| accessdate=2010-12-06| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101207022646/http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/12/discover-more-than-3-million-google.html| archivedate= 7 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
